		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>Ryten, I agree with most of what you said, but I think that if you want an honest discussion, we ened to start from what is the real problem.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Never befora has such imbalance existed between hardcore and casual players. I am most familiar with my class, the necromancer. After 4 years of "casual" (I call it casual, but 2 hrs a night is casual only by EQ standards...) play - and lots of slacking - my necro is lev 65 with 50 aas. I have 2.5k hps unbuffed, about 4k mana, a couple of focus effects which lead me to save 10 percent of my mana on casts about and to do 10 pcnt more dmg.&nbsp;One of my friends is a time enabled raiding&nbsp;necro, with about 7k hps, about 6k mana, focuses up the ying-yang - 25% dmg improvement on dots or dds through those "specific" focuses from GoD, mana preservation items, clickies that nuke for more than i can ans AAs that lead to all sorts of other, less easily quantifiable, advantages. Just today I saw a "theoretical" necro profile (one of those "best case magelos") with over 8k hps unbuffed). </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Now, please do not get me wrong.... there is nothing wrong with someone who spends more time online and more time riding having better items. But they are getting more expansions that the rest of the playerbase is (see PoP &amp; GoD, both almost exclusively aimed at the raiding player). Every expansions raises the bar - and it has to, because if you do not put rewards in that are improvements, how are you going to attract those people?</DIV>
<DIV>Hence the imbalances - one part of the playerbase is improving over time at a much faster pace than the rest of the population (after all, I probably have now 25% more hps than I had 2 years ago - i went from 2k to 2.5k. My raiding buddy, in the same time, went from 3k to 7k - we are lacking&nbsp;some sense of scale here). </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>So, if you ask me,&nbsp;nothing will&nbsp;fix things until those core imbalances are addressed. But I suppose its always easier to throw in a couple of 200+&nbsp;mana/hp items in the game than to design a really interesting zone - and we know both have the same effects - keeping people in the game. &nbsp;</DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							There is no Zerp. 
Not on SZ, at least.
							</div>
								
